		<td width="10%" nowrap="nowrap">Post subject:&nbsp;</td>
		<td><b>Flash Chips memory organization &amp; Microcontrollers Question</b></td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
		<td colspan="2"><hr class="sep" />Hello,<br /><br />I want to be able to flash my chips over USB Fast! While doing research I come across some questions.<br /><br />I once built a GB Flasher that used an 8bit microcontroller (ATmega8515), and I've noticed that the all of the flash roms that are recommended for Gameboy and SNES are organized by 8 sections. IE a 4Mbit memory, 512K x 8 it will say for the datasheet, or 32 Mbit, 4Mbit x 8.<br /><br />My 2 questions are 1:<br /><br />1) Does the flash have to be organized in that way? I've seen other Flash memory out here (can't remember anything off the top of my head), and I scratched my head and wondered if they couldn't work? <br /><br />2) What about using a 32bit micro controller for this line of work? Is that overkill? I ask because not much is coming up when i search for a micro controller and High-Speed USB, except for beefy chips.<br /><br />Thanks in advance,<br />Bazz

		

		</td>
	</tr>
	</table>


	<hr width="85%" />

	<table width="85%" cellspacing="3" cellpadding="0" border="0" align="center">
