	<tr>
		<td width="10%" nowrap="nowrap">Post subject:&nbsp;</td>
		<td><b>Re: Flash Chips memory organization &amp; Microcontrollers Quest</b></td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
		<td colspan="2"><hr class="sep" />The &quot;x8&quot; may just refer to 8 bits per byte. On the Super NES, you want x8 memory unless a coprocessor needs x16. On the Genesis, you always want x16 because its CPU has a 16-bit data bus. There will also be a size of &quot;erase blocks&quot; that defines the smallest amount you can reprogram at once.

		

		</td>
	</tr>
	</table>


